          <msContents>
            <summary>[i]Liber mineralium[/i]. Books I and II only and one page of Book III. (There are five Books comprising the published original). [/p]

[p]Written in a small neat humanistic hand, 28 lines to a page.[/p]

[p]Fol. 1 (Beginning of Book I) BEATI ALBERTI MAGNI GERMANICI PHILOSOPHI /CELEBERRIMI MINERALIVM LIBER INCIPIT ET/PRIMO DE LAPIDIBVS LIBER PRIMVS FOELICITER [D]E COMMIXTIONE et coagulatione similiter autem et conge/latione et liquefactione ... to fol. 39 (End of Book II) ... sed quedam portio/nes de libro excepte deuenerunt.[/p]
[p]Fol. 39v (Beginning of Book III) TEMPVS autem est nunc [consequenter] de metallorum naturis inquirere post la/pidum inuestigationem... line 28 ... in communi querentes quicumque de natura metallorum uidebuntur esse inquirenda Libro complebimus. Only one page of text from book three is in this manuscript.[/p] </summary>
            <textLang mainLang="" source="IANA">Latin</textLang>
            <msItem n="1" xml:id="MS_14_1">
              <author>Saint Albertus Magnus, d. 1280</author>
              <title type="original">Saint Albertus Magnus (d. 1280)</title>
              <title type="standard"/>
              <textLang mainLang="" source="IANA">Latin</textLang>
              <filiation>This work was first printed at Padua in 1476. On the second fly-leaf is a note in pencil 'Alberti Magni MS. 1474', but no date can be found in this manuscript as it exists at present. On the first fly-leaf is a signature 'Barba' by an early 17th cent. hand, which may possibly be that of Alvaro Alonso Barba, the metallurgist and author of 'Arte de los metales', Madrid, 1640.</filiation>
              <filiation/>
            </msItem>
          </msContents>
